<DOC><DOCNO> AP880323-0249 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0238EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-23 0512</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0536</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Higher postage rates, including a 25-centcharge for first-class letters, will take effect April 3, thePostal Service says.   The new rates, announced Tuesday, reflect higher costs ofdelivering mail, said John L. Griesemer, chairman of the PostalService Board of Governors.   The board set the effective date for the sweeping series of newrates recommended by the independent Postal Rate Commission earlierthis month. Rates were last changed in February 1985, when theprice of a first-class stamp rose to 22 cents from 20 cents.</TEXT><DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Dissident stockholders dropped theiropposition to Texaco Inc.'s financial reorganization plan as afederal judge opened a hearing on whether to implement the proposal.   Texaco, the nation's third largest oil company, announcedTuesday that the plan was overwhelmingly supported in a vote byshareholders. Some 96 percent of the 181 million shares votedbacked the plan, which would allow the company to emerge frombankruptcy court protection.   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard Schwartzberg heard commentson the plan from various parties, and recessed the hearing untiltoday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Campeau Corp. has sweetened its bid forFederated Department Stores Inc. and proposed a friendly mergerwith the retailer.   Campeau raised its two-tier, all-cash offer to approximately $73a share, or $6.53 billion, on Tuesday from $68 a share, or $6.18billion.   At the same time, Campeau extended the deadline for expirationof its offer until midnight EST April 4, when a competing $6.3billion tender offer by R.H. Macy andamp; Co. Inc. that Federated hasaccepted is also due to expire.</TEXT><DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Stores Co. has offered $1.72billion to acquire Lucky Stores Inc. of California in a deal thatwould create one of the nation's largest supermarket and discountdrug chains.   The $45-per-share bid announced Tuesday for Lucky Stores camesome 16 months after Lucky derailed a hostile takeover attempt byNew York investor Asher Edelman.   The latest unsolicited offer sent Lucky's stock soaring by$14.50 a share to $46.37{ on the New York Stock Exchange.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Black andamp; Decker Corp. has withdrawn its$77-a-share bid for American Standard Inc., halting the bidding warover the plumbing giant.   Tuesday's action permits a $78-a-share leveraged buyout ofAmerican Standard, spearheaded by Kelso andamp; Co. and valued at $2.45billion, to go forward.   Under the agreement, Kelso will pay Black andamp; Decker $25 millionfor withdrawing its bid, as soon as Kelso begins purchasing stockunder its tender offer or acquires at least 20 percent of AmericanStandard's shares in any other transaction.</TEXT><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Koppers Co. has rejected a revised cash tenderoffer of $56 a share, or about $1.6 billion, from a takeovercompany formed by Britain's Brian Beazer and the U.S. investmentfirm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.   Koppers Chairman Charles R. Pullin said Tuesday that theKoppers' board believes remaining independent ``is a superioralternative to accepting'' the revised offer from Beazer's BNS Inc.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>